@@TOPIC overview
@@GROUP general
@@BRIEF Identity, architecture, and quick start guide.
@@RELATED flags, examples, --agent, --run-source

agent86 is a 16-bit x86 real-mode assembler and emulator that produces and executes
flat .COM binaries. It is a two-pass assembler written in C++ with a built-in 8086 CPU
emulator, both with structured JSON output designed for agentic AI consumption.

Target architecture: Intel 8086/8088 (with optional 80186 extensions)
Output format:       Flat binary (.COM), loaded at offset 0100h
Max address space:   65,535 bytes (one 64KB segment)
Assembly pipeline:   expandIncludes() -> expandMacros() -> two-pass assembly

Windows note: Run agent86 directly -- do NOT wrap in cmd.exe /c, as the cmd startup
banner contaminates JSON output.

PowerShell 5.x encoding trap: The > redirect in PS 5.x re-encodes output as UTF-16LE,
breaking JSON parsers. Use --output-file result.json instead, or upgrade to PS 7+.

@@EXAMPLES
agent86 --agent hello.asm
agent86 --run-source hello.asm
agent86 --run hello.com
agent86 --disassemble output.com
agent86 --explain MOV
agent86 --dump-isa
agent86 --help [topic]
@@END

@@TOPIC flags
@@GROUP general
@@BRIEF All CLI flags at a glance.
@@RELATED overview, examples

Assembler flags:
  --agent               Primary assembly mode. JSON report to stdout.
  --disassemble         Disassemble .COM binary to structured JSON.
  --explain <MNEMONIC>  Query ISA knowledge base for one instruction.
  --dump-isa            Dump entire supported instruction set as JSON.
  (no flags)            Human-readable mode. Not recommended for agents.

Emulator flags:
  --run <file.com>      Run a .COM binary in the emulator.
  --run-source <f.asm>  Assemble and run in one step.
  --breakpoints <a,b>   Set breakpoints at hex addresses (comma-separated).
  --watch-regs <r,r>    Watch registers for changes. Emits snapshots.
  --max-cycles <N>      Maximum CPU cycles before forced halt. Default: 1000000.
  --input <string>      Stdin input for INT 21h/01h,06h. Escapes: \xHH \0 \n \r \t \\ \S
  --args <string>       Command-line tail written to PSP at offset 80h.
  --mem-dump <addr,len> Memory dump in breakpoint snapshots. Addr=hex, len=decimal.
  --output-file <path>  Write JSON to file instead of stdout.

Screen capture flags:
  --screen              Capture full 80x50 screen from VRAM.
  --viewport <c,r,w,h>  Capture a rectangular region of the screen.
  --attrs               Include attribute bytes in screen output.
  --screenshot <f.bmp>  Render VRAM as a 24-bit BMP image file.
  --font 8x8|8x16      Font size for screenshot. Default: 8x16.
  --vram-fill [text]    Pre-fill VRAM before program runs.

Interaction flags:
  --mouse <x,y[,btn]>   Configure mouse state for INT 33h.
  --events <JSON|@file>  Script timeline of user interactions.
  --dos-root <dir>       Mount host directory as DOS filesystem root (C:\).

Help:
  --help                List all help topics.
  --help <topic>        Show detailed help for a specific topic.

@@END

@@TOPIC examples
@@GROUP general
@@BRIEF Common usage patterns and command examples.
@@RELATED flags, overview, --agent, --run-source

A collection of common command-line patterns for agent86.

@@EXAMPLES
agent86 --agent myprogram.asm
agent86 --run-source myprogram.asm
agent86 --run-source prog.asm --breakpoints 0120,0135 --watch-regs AX,DX
agent86 --run-source prog.asm --input "Hello"
agent86 --run output.com --breakpoints 0100 --mem-dump 0200,64
agent86 --explain IMUL
agent86 --dump-isa
agent86 --disassemble output.com
agent86 --run-source life.asm --screen
agent86 --run-source life.asm --viewport 0,0,40,25 --attrs
agent86 --run-source life.asm --screenshot screen.bmp --font 8x8
agent86 --run-source game.asm --vram-fill "ABCD" --screen
agent86 --run-source app.asm --events '[{"on":"poll:3","mouse":[320,100,1]},{"on":"read:1","keys":"Y"}]'
agent86 --run-source app.asm --events @events.json
agent86 --run-source filetest.asm --dos-root ./testdir
agent86 --run-source life.asm --screen --output-file result.json
agent86 --run-source prog.asm --args "param1 param2"
@@END

@@TOPIC --agent
@@GROUP assembly
@@BRIEF Primary assembly mode. Structured JSON report to stdout.
@@RELATED --run-source, --disassemble, json-agent, errors, warnings

Assemble a source file and emit structured JSON with diagnostics, listing, and symbols.

Output JSON fields:
  success       true/false -- whether a binary was produced
  diagnostics[] errors/warnings with level, line, msg, and actionable hint
  symbols{}     complete symbol table (name -> val, type, line, file)
  listing[]     per-instruction details (addr, bytes, decoded, src, size)
  includes[]    list of all source files involved

Always read diagnostics[].hint first -- every diagnostic includes an actionable fix.
Verify listing[].decoded matches your intent to detect misparsed instructions.

@@EXAMPLES
agent86 --agent source.asm
@@END

@@TOPIC --run
@@GROUP emulation
@@BRIEF Run a pre-compiled .COM binary in the emulator.
@@RELATED --run-source, json-run, debugging, screen-capture

Run a .COM binary and emit emulation results as JSON.

The JSON output is the emulation section as a top-level object (same fields as
--run-source emulation, plus finalState.sregs and finalState.flagBits).

Combine with --breakpoints, --watch-regs, --screen, --viewport, --attrs,
--screenshot, --mouse, --events, --dos-root, --input, --args, --mem-dump.

@@EXAMPLES
agent86 --run program.com
agent86 --run program.com --breakpoints 0110,0120
agent86 --run program.com --screen --attrs
agent86 --run program.com --input "Hello\n"
@@END

@@TOPIC --run-source
@@GROUP emulation
@@BRIEF Assemble and run in one step. Combined JSON output.
@@RELATED --agent, --run, json-run, debugging

Assemble a source file and immediately run the binary in the emulator.

Output JSON contains two top-level sections:
  assembly.success       whether assembly succeeded
  assembly.size          binary size in bytes
  assembly.diagnostics[] assembly errors/warnings
  emulation.*            all emulation fields (see json-run topic)

If assembly fails, the emulation section has success:false with no meaningful state.

Workflow:
  1. Write .asm source
  2. Run: agent86 --run-source source.asm
  3. If assembly.success == false: read diagnostics, fix, retry
  4. If assembly.success == true: check emulation.output, emulation.haltReason

@@EXAMPLES
agent86 --run-source source.asm
agent86 --run-source source.asm --screen
agent86 --run-source source.asm --breakpoints 0110 --watch-regs AX
@@END

@@TOPIC --disassemble
@@GROUP assembly
@@BRIEF Disassemble a .COM binary to structured JSON.
@@RELATED --agent, json-disassemble

Read a flat .COM binary and emit a JSON disassembly. Primary round-trip verification
tool: assemble with --agent, then disassemble to confirm bytes decode correctly.

Output JSON fields:
  file             input filename
  fileSize         total binary size in bytes
  instructions[]   decoded instructions (addr, bytes, hex, asm, size)
  dataRegions[]    bytes that could not be decoded as instructions

The disassembler uses linear sweep (sequential from offset 0, not control-flow).
Immediates displayed as uppercase hex with 0x prefix. Jump targets shown as absolute
addresses. String data (DB) appears in dataRegions.

@@EXAMPLES
agent86 --disassemble output.com
agent86 --agent source.asm && agent86 --disassemble source.com
@@END

@@TOPIC --explain
@@GROUP assembly
@@BRIEF Query ISA knowledge base for one instruction's valid forms.
@@RELATED --dump-isa, instructions

Query the ISA database for all valid operand forms of a given mnemonic.

Output JSON:
  { "mnemonic":"MOV", "found":true, "forms":[
    {"op1":"REG","op2":"REG","notes":""},
    {"op1":"REG","op2":"IMM","notes":""},
    ...
  ]}

Operand type codes:
  REG     any general-purpose register (8 or 16 bit)
  REG8    8-bit only (AL,CL,DL,BL,AH,CH,DH,BH)
  REG16   16-bit only (AX,CX,DX,BX,SP,BP,SI,DI)
  MEM     memory operand ([BX], [BX+SI+4], etc.)
  IMM     immediate value, label, or expression
  LABEL   same as IMM, indicates relative addressing
  SREG    segment register (ES,CS,SS,DS)
  AL/AX   accumulator specifically
  CL      CL register specifically
  DX      DX register specifically
  1       literal constant 1
  NONE    no operand in this position

@@EXAMPLES
agent86 --explain MOV
agent86 --explain IMUL
agent86 --explain PUSH
@@END

@@TOPIC --dump-isa
@@GROUP assembly
@@BRIEF Dump the entire supported instruction set as JSON.
@@RELATED --explain, instructions

List all supported mnemonics with descriptions.

Output: JSON array of objects with mnemonic and desc fields.

@@EXAMPLES
agent86 --dump-isa
@@END

@@TOPIC --breakpoints
@@GROUP debugging
@@BRIEF Set breakpoints at hex addresses for state capture.
@@RELATED --watch-regs, --mem-dump, debugging

Set breakpoints at specific addresses. When execution reaches a breakpoint, the
emulator captures a full CPU state snapshot.

Each snapshot contains:
  addr       IP where breakpoint fired (hex)
  cycle      instruction count when hit
  reason     e.g. "Breakpoint at 0x0110"
  nextInst   disassembly of instruction about to execute
  registers  all 8 registers as hex
  flags      flags register as hex
  cursor     VRAM cursor position {row, col}
  stack      top 8 words from stack
  memDump    hex string of memory region (if --mem-dump configured)
  screen[]   screen text (if --screen/--viewport used)
  hitCount   times this address has been hit

Limits: 10 full snapshots per address, 100 total. After 10 hits at one address,
only hitCount increments on the last snapshot.

@@EXAMPLES
agent86 --run-source prog.asm --breakpoints 0110,0120
agent86 --run prog.com --breakpoints 0100,0150 --mem-dump 0200,32
agent86 --run-source life.asm --breakpoints 0150 --screen
@@END

@@TOPIC --watch-regs
@@GROUP debugging
@@BRIEF Watch registers for changes. Emits snapshots on change.
@@RELATED --breakpoints, --mem-dump, debugging

When a watched register changes value, a snapshot is emitted.

Valid register names: AX, CX, DX, BX, SP, BP, SI, DI (case-insensitive).

Snapshot reason format: "AX changed: 0x0005 -> 0x0006"

Combine with --breakpoints for both positional and data-flow debugging.

@@EXAMPLES
agent86 --run-source prog.asm --watch-regs AX,DX,CX
agent86 --run-source prog.asm --breakpoints 0110 --watch-regs AX,BX
@@END

@@TOPIC --max-cycles
@@GROUP emulation
@@BRIEF Maximum CPU cycles before forced halt. Default: 1000000.
@@RELATED --run, --run-source

Set the maximum number of instructions the emulator will execute before halting.

Default is 1,000,000 cycles. When hit, haltReason = "Cycle limit reached (N)".
Use cyclesExecuted in the output to detect infinite loops (will equal --max-cycles).

@@EXAMPLES
agent86 --run-source prog.asm --max-cycles 5000
agent86 --run prog.com --max-cycles 500000
@@END

@@TOPIC --mem-dump
@@GROUP debugging
@@BRIEF Include memory dump in breakpoint snapshots.
@@RELATED --breakpoints, --watch-regs, debugging

When combined with breakpoints, each snapshot includes a hex dump of a memory region.

Format: --mem-dump <hex_addr>,<decimal_length>
The memDump field in each snapshot is a hex string of the specified region.

@@EXAMPLES
agent86 --run-source prog.asm --breakpoints 0110 --mem-dump 0200,32
agent86 --run prog.com --breakpoints 0100 --mem-dump 0200,64
@@END

@@TOPIC --input
@@GROUP interaction
@@BRIEF Provide stdin input for the program.
@@RELATED --args, --events, interaction

Provide text input consumed by INT 21h/01h (read with echo) and INT 21h/06h (direct
console I/O with DL=FFh).

Supported escape sequences:
  \xHH   hex byte
  \0     null byte
  \n     newline (0Ah)
  \r     carriage return (0Dh)
  \t     tab (09h)
  \\     literal backslash
  \S     shift-held prefix (sets Left Shift flag for the next byte)

When input is exhausted, INT 21h/01h returns 0Dh (Enter).

Shift prefix:
  \SA          delivers 'A' with Left Shift held
  \S\x00\S\x4B  delivers extended key pair 00h,4Bh with shift held

@@EXAMPLES
agent86 --run-source prog.asm --input "Hello\n"
agent86 --run-source prog.asm --input "\x00\x4B"
agent86 --run-source arrows.asm --input "\S\x00\S\x4B"
@@END

@@TOPIC --args
@@GROUP interaction
@@BRIEF Command-line arguments written to PSP command tail.
@@RELATED --input, --run-source

Provide a command-line tail string written to the PSP at offset 80h (length byte)
and 81h+ (content with leading space, terminated by CR), following DOS convention.

Maximum 126 characters. The program reads PSP:80h for length and PSP:81h for content.

@@EXAMPLES
agent86 --run-source prog.asm --args "param1 param2"
@@END

@@TOPIC --output-file
@@GROUP general
@@BRIEF Write JSON output to a file instead of stdout.
@@RELATED flags

Write all JSON output to a file, bypassing shell encoding issues.

This avoids PowerShell 5.x UTF-16LE re-encoding and BOM insertion that breaks JSON
parsers. Recommended whenever capturing output on Windows.

@@EXAMPLES
agent86 --run-source prog.asm --screen --output-file result.json
agent86 --run-source life.asm --screen --attrs --output-file frames.json
@@END

@@TOPIC --screen
@@GROUP screen-capture
@@BRIEF Capture full 80x50 screen from VRAM into JSON output.
@@RELATED --viewport, --attrs, --screenshot, --font, --vram-fill, screen-capture

Capture the full 80x50 CGA text-mode VRAM screen.

Adds screen[] to output: array of 50 strings, each 80 characters wide.
Non-printable bytes replaced with '.' for clean JSON.

Also included in breakpoint snapshots when used with --breakpoints.

@@EXAMPLES
agent86 --run-source life.asm --screen
agent86 --run-source life.asm --screen --attrs
agent86 --run-source life.asm --screen --breakpoints 0150
@@END

@@TOPIC --viewport
@@GROUP screen-capture
@@BRIEF Capture a rectangular region of the screen.
@@RELATED --screen, --attrs, --screenshot, screen-capture

Capture a sub-region of the 80x50 VRAM screen.

Format: --viewport <col>,<row>,<width>,<height>

Adds screen[] to output with rows of the specified width.

@@EXAMPLES
agent86 --run-source life.asm --viewport 0,0,40,25
agent86 --run-source life.asm --viewport 10,5,20,10 --attrs
agent86 --run-source life.asm --viewport 0,0,40,25 --breakpoints 0150
@@END

@@TOPIC --attrs
@@GROUP screen-capture
@@BRIEF Include CGA attribute bytes in screen output.
@@RELATED --screen, --viewport, attributes, screen-capture

Include attribute data alongside screen text.

Adds screenAttrs[] parallel to screen[]. Each string has two hex digits per cell
representing the CGA attribute byte (e.g. "07" = light grey on black, "1F" = white
on blue).

@@EXAMPLES
agent86 --run-source colors.asm --screen --attrs
agent86 --run-source vram_hi.asm --viewport 0,0,10,1 --attrs
@@END

@@TOPIC --screenshot
@@GROUP screen-capture
@@BRIEF Render VRAM as a 24-bit BMP image file.
@@RELATED --font, --screen, screen-capture

Render the VRAM contents as a BMP image using CP437 fonts with CGA 16-color palette.

Output resolution depends on --font:
  8x16 (default): 640x800 pixels
  8x8:            640x400 pixels

The screenshot field in JSON contains the output file path on success.

@@EXAMPLES
agent86 --run-source life.asm --screenshot screen.bmp
agent86 --run-source life.asm --screenshot screen.bmp --font 8x8
@@END

@@TOPIC --font
@@GROUP screen-capture
@@BRIEF Select font size for BMP screenshot rendering.
@@RELATED --screenshot, screen-capture

Choose between 8x8 and 8x16 pixel fonts for --screenshot rendering.

  8x16 (default)  640x800 pixels, taller characters
  8x8             640x400 pixels, more compact

@@EXAMPLES
agent86 --run-source life.asm --screenshot screen.bmp --font 8x8
agent86 --run-source life.asm --screenshot screen.bmp --font 8x16
@@END

@@TOPIC --vram-fill
@@GROUP screen-capture
@@BRIEF Pre-fill VRAM with known content before program runs.
@@RELATED --screen, --viewport, screen-capture

Pre-fill all 4000 VRAM character cells with a known pattern before the program runs.
Useful for identifying which cells a program actually writes to.

With text argument: tiles the string across all cells. Attribute bytes stay at 07h.
Without argument: fills with random printable characters.

Any cell still showing the fill pattern was never written by the program.

@@EXAMPLES
agent86 --run-source game.asm --vram-fill "." --screen
agent86 --run-source game.asm --vram-fill "ABCD" --screen
agent86 --run-source game.asm --vram-fill --screen
@@END

@@TOPIC --mouse
@@GROUP interaction
@@BRIEF Configure initial mouse state for INT 33h emulation.
@@RELATED --events, int33h, interaction

Set the initial mouse position and button state. Presence enables the mouse driver.

Format: --mouse <x>,<y>[,<buttons>]
  x,y       pixel coordinates
  buttons   bitmask: 1=left, 2=right, 4=middle (default: 0)

When enabled, INT 33h/0000h returns AX=FFFFh (driver installed).
Without --mouse or --events with mouse actions, INT 33h returns AX=0 (not installed).

@@EXAMPLES
agent86 --run-source menu.asm --mouse 320,100,1
agent86 --run-source draw.asm --mouse 160,50,0
@@END

@@TOPIC --events
@@GROUP interaction
@@BRIEF Script a timeline of keyboard and mouse interactions.
@@RELATED --mouse, --input, interaction

Script coordinated keyboard/mouse interactions triggered by program behavior.

Trigger types (each event fires once when counter reaches the value):
  read:N     Nth INT 21h keyboard read (AH=01h or 06h/DL=FFh)
  poll:N     Nth INT 33h/0003h mouse position poll
  tick:N     After Nth CPU cycle
  int21:N    Nth INT 21h call (any function)
  int33:N    Nth INT 33h call (any function)

Action types (combinable per event):
  mouse      [x, y, buttons]   Set mouse state. Auto-enables driver.
  keys       "string"          Inject bytes into keyboard buffer.
  snapshot   true              Capture CPU/memory snapshot.

Keys support escapes: \xHH \n \r \t \0 \\ \S (shift prefix)

JSON output includes events object: total, fired, pending, log[].

@@EXAMPLES
agent86 --run-source app.asm --events '[{"on":"poll:3","mouse":[320,100,1]},{"on":"read:1","keys":"Y"}]'
agent86 --run-source app.asm --events @events.json
agent86 --run-source app.asm --events '[{"on":"poll:5","mouse":[320,100,1],"snapshot":true},{"on":"poll:10","mouse":[320,100,0]},{"on":"read:1","keys":"Y"}]'
@@END

@@TOPIC --dos-root
@@GROUP file-io
@@BRIEF Mount a host directory as DOS filesystem root for file I/O.
@@RELATED file-io, int21h

Mount a host directory as the DOS C:\ drive, enabling INT 21h file operations.

Enables: create (3Ch), open (3Dh), close (3Eh), read (3Fh), write (40h),
seek (42h), attributes (43h), chdir (3Bh), getcwd (47h), FindFirst (4Eh),
FindNext (4Fh).

Path sandboxing:
  - Drive letters stripped: C:\FILE.TXT becomes FILE.TXT relative to root
  - Backslashes normalized to forward slashes
  - Relative paths use current directory (set by AH=3Bh)
  - Directory traversal blocked: .. cannot escape the root
  - Canonical path validation ensures containment

Without --dos-root, all file/directory functions return CF=1, AX=2 (file not found).
Console I/O and system functions work regardless.

@@EXAMPLES
agent86 --run-source fileapp.asm --dos-root ./testdir
agent86 --run-source reader.asm --dos-root /path/to/files
agent86 --run-source fileapp.asm --dos-root ./data --breakpoints 0120 --watch-regs AX,BX
@@END

@@TOPIC debugging
@@GROUP debugging
@@BRIEF Breakpoints, watchpoints, and memory dumps for debugging.
@@RELATED --breakpoints, --watch-regs, --mem-dump, screen-capture

Combined reference for all debugging features.

Breakpoints: Set with --breakpoints <hex_addr,...>
  Capture full CPU state snapshot when IP reaches the address.
  10 full snapshots per address, 100 total.

Watchpoints: Set with --watch-regs <reg,...>
  Snapshot emitted when a watched register changes value.
  Valid: AX, CX, DX, BX, SP, BP, SI, DI

Memory dumps: Set with --mem-dump <hex_addr>,<decimal_len>
  Each breakpoint snapshot includes hex dump of the specified region.

Debugging workflow:
  1. Find suspect address from --agent listing[].addr
  2. Run with --breakpoints at that address
  3. Inspect snapshots[].registers, .nextInst, .stack
  4. Add --watch-regs to trace data flow
  5. Add --mem-dump to inspect memory at each breakpoint
  6. For VRAM programs, add --screen to capture display at each snapshot

@@EXAMPLES
agent86 --agent source.asm
agent86 --run-source prog.asm --breakpoints 0110,0120 --watch-regs AX,DX --mem-dump 0200,32
agent86 --run-source life.asm --viewport 0,0,40,25 --breakpoints 0150
agent86 --run-source life.asm --screen --breakpoints 0150 --output-file frames.json
@@END

@@TOPIC screen-capture
@@GROUP screen-capture
@@BRIEF Screen, viewport, attrs, screenshot, font, and vram-fill together.
@@RELATED --screen, --viewport, --attrs, --screenshot, --font, --vram-fill

Combined reference for all screen capture features.

The emulator provides an 8KB VRAM buffer (segment B800h, 80x50 CGA text mode).
Each cell is 2 bytes: character + attribute. Programs write via ES:DI or INT 10h.

Capture flags:
  --screen              Full 80x50 capture -> screen[] in JSON
  --viewport c,r,w,h    Sub-region capture -> screen[] in JSON
  --attrs               Add screenAttrs[] parallel to screen[]
  --screenshot f.bmp    Render to BMP image (CP437 + CGA 16 colors)
  --font 8x8|8x16      Font size for BMP (default 8x16)
  --vram-fill [text]    Pre-fill VRAM to detect which cells programs write

screen[] is an array of strings, one per row. Non-printable bytes -> '.'
screenAttrs[] has two hex digits per cell (e.g. "07" = light grey on black).

Screen data is included in breakpoint snapshots too, enabling frame-by-frame
inspection of VRAM programs (games, animations).

@@EXAMPLES
agent86 --run-source life.asm --screen
agent86 --run-source life.asm --viewport 0,0,40,25 --attrs
agent86 --run-source life.asm --screenshot screen.bmp --font 8x8
agent86 --run-source game.asm --vram-fill "." --screen
agent86 --run-source life.asm --viewport 0,0,40,25 --attrs --breakpoints 0150
@@END

@@TOPIC interaction
@@GROUP interaction
@@BRIEF Mouse, events, input, and args together.
@@RELATED --mouse, --events, --input, --args

Combined reference for all user interaction features.

Keyboard input: --input <string>
  Consumed by INT 21h/01h and 06h. Supports \xHH \0 \n \r \t \\ \S escapes.

Command-line args: --args <string>
  Written to PSP at 80h (length) and 81h+ (content with leading space + CR).

Mouse state: --mouse <x>,<y>[,<buttons>]
  Sets initial mouse position. Enables INT 33h driver.

Event scripting: --events <JSON|@file>
  Triggers: read:N, poll:N, tick:N, int21:N, int33:N
  Actions: mouse, keys, snapshot

Composability: --events works with --input and --mouse. Event-injected keys insert
at the current read position. Events can override mouse state set by --mouse.

Workflow for interactive programs:
  1. First run with no events to see what the program expects
  2. Add read:N triggers for keyboard prompts
  3. Add poll:N triggers for mouse interactions
  4. Attach snapshot:true to key moments
  5. Check events.pending to see if all events fired

@@EXAMPLES
agent86 --run-source prog.asm --input "Hello\n"
agent86 --run-source prog.asm --args "param1 param2"
agent86 --run-source menu.asm --mouse 320,100,1
agent86 --run-source app.asm --events '[{"on":"poll:3","mouse":[320,100,1]},{"on":"read:1","keys":"Y"}]'
agent86 --run-source app.asm --events @events.json
@@END

@@TOPIC file-io
@@GROUP file-io
@@BRIEF DOS file I/O, DTA layout, path sandboxing.
@@RELATED --dos-root, int21h

File handle I/O requires --dos-root to be set (except device handles 0-4).

Device handles (always available):
  0  STDIN   reads from --input buffer
  1  STDOUT  writes to output/VRAM
  2  STDERR  writes to output/VRAM
  3  AUX     discarded
  4  PRN     discarded

File operations (require --dos-root):
  AH=3Ch  Create/truncate file  DS:DX=path, CX=attrs -> AX=handle
  AH=3Dh  Open file             DS:DX=path, AL=mode  -> AX=handle
  AH=3Eh  Close file            BX=handle
  AH=3Fh  Read file             BX=handle, CX=count, DS:DX=buf -> AX=read
  AH=40h  Write file            BX=handle, CX=count, DS:DX=buf -> AX=written
  AH=42h  Seek                  BX=handle, AL=origin, CX:DX=offset -> DX:AX=pos
  AH=43h  Get/set attributes    AL=0:get, AL=1:set
  AH=57h  Get file date/time    AL=0, BX=handle -> CX=time, DX=date

Directory operations (require --dos-root):
  AH=3Bh  Change directory      DS:DX=path
  AH=47h  Get current directory  DS:SI=buffer, DL=drive
  AH=4Eh  FindFirst             DS:DX=pattern, CX=attr mask -> writes DTA
  AH=4Fh  FindNext              continues previous FindFirst -> writes DTA

Error convention: CF=1 on failure, AX=error code.
  1=invalid function, 2=file not found, 3=path not found,
  5=access denied, 6=invalid handle, 18=no more files

DTA layout (43 bytes, set with AH=1Ah, default at PSP:0080h):
  00h  21 bytes  Reserved (search state)
  15h  1 byte    File attribute (10h=directory, 20h=file)
  16h  2 bytes   Packed time (hrs:5|min:6|sec/2:5)
  18h  2 bytes   Packed date (yr-1980:7|mon:4|day:5)
  1Ah  4 bytes   File size (DWORD, little-endian)
  1Eh  13 bytes  Filename in 8.3 format, null-terminated

FindFirst CX mask: 00h=files only, 10h=files+dirs, 02h=files+hidden, 16h=all

Wildcard matching (DOS conventions, case-insensitive, 8.3 format):
  *.*     all entries
  *.TXT   .TXT extension only
  DATA.*  DATA with any extension
  FILE?   single-char wildcard

@@EXAMPLES
agent86 --run-source reader.asm --dos-root ./testdir
agent86 --run-source writer.asm --dos-root ./testdir
agent86 --run-source dirlist.asm --dos-root ./myfiles
@@END

@@TOPIC syntax
@@GROUP reference
@@BRIEF Registers, numeric literals, labels, memory operands, expressions.
@@RELATED addressing, directives, instructions

Registers:
  8-bit:   AL, CL, DL, BL, AH, CH, DH, BH
  16-bit:  AX, CX, DX, BX, SP, BP, SI, DI
  Segment: ES, CS, SS, DS
  All names are case-insensitive.

Numeric literals:
  Decimal:       100, 100d
  Hex (suffix):  0FFh, 100h       MUST start with digit (0FFh not FFh)
  Hex (prefix):  0xFF
  Binary:        10110b, 0b10110
  Octal:         177o, 177q

Labels:
  start:          global label (visible everywhere)
  myproc: PROC
  .loop:          local label (scoped to enclosing PROC, stored as MYPROC.LOOP)
  ENDP

Labels require colon syntax on their own line. Case-insensitive (stored uppercase).
Local labels (. prefix) require enclosing PROC/ENDP block.

Memory operands:
  [100h]           direct address
  [BX]             base register
  [BX+4]           base + displacement
  [BX+SI]          base + index
  [BX+SI+10h]      base + index + displacement
  [BP+DI]          BP-based (defaults to SS segment)

Segment overrides:
  MOV AX, ES:[BX]
  MOV AX, [ES:BX]

Size prefixes (required for memory-immediate operations):
  MOV BYTE [BX], 5      8-bit store
  MOV WORD [BX], 5      16-bit store
  Without prefix, assembler defaults to WORD and emits a WARNING.

Expressions:
  Operators: + - * / (integer division), unary -, parentheses
  Special: $ = current address counter

Comments: ; begins a comment to end of line.

@@EXAMPLES
MOV CX, BUFSIZE * 2
JMP $ + 5
MOV AX, (BUFSIZE + 4) / 2
@@END

@@TOPIC directives
@@GROUP reference
@@BRIEF ORG, DB/DW/DD, RESB/RESW, EQU, PROC/ENDP, INCLUDE.
@@RELATED syntax, macros, structs

ORG <addr>       Set address counter. Use ORG 100h for .COM files.
DB <vals>        Define bytes. Strings, numbers, expressions, comma-separated.
DW <vals>        Define 16-bit words (little-endian).
DD <vals>        Define 32-bit doublewords (little-endian).
RESB <n>         Reserve n zero-initialized bytes.
RESW <n>         Reserve n zero-initialized words (n*2 zero bytes).
EQU              Define compile-time constant: BUFSIZE EQU 256
PROC             Begin named procedure: myproc: PROC (enables local labels)
ENDP             End current procedure scope.
INCLUDE          Insert another source file: INCLUDE 'file.asm'

INCLUDE details:
  Syntax: INCLUDE 'file.asm', INCLUDE "file.asm", INCLUDE file.inc
  Path resolution: relative to the including file's directory
  Nesting: up to 16 levels deep; circular includes detected
  Case-insensitive keyword

Data directives go after a label defined on a separate line:
  msg:
      DB 'Hello', 0

@@EXAMPLES
ORG 100h
DB 'Hello', 0Dh, 0Ah, '$'
DW 1234h, label_addr
RESB 64
BUFSIZE EQU 256
INCLUDE 'data.asm'
@@END

@@TOPIC macros
@@GROUP reference
@@BRIEF MACRO/ENDM, LOCAL, REPT, IRP, nesting, concatenation.
@@RELATED directives, syntax

Macros are expanded as a text-level preprocessor step after INCLUDE expansion but
before two-pass assembly. Pipeline: expandIncludes() -> expandMacros() -> assembly.

Named macros:
  name MACRO [param1, param2, ...]
  ... body ...
  ENDM

Substitution: case-insensitive, word-boundary only, strings/comments protected.
Name appears before MACRO keyword. Invoke by using macro name as instruction.

& concatenation (consumed during substitution):
  name&num: joins parameter text with surrounding characters.

LOCAL labels (unique ??XXXX names per expansion):
  LOCAL must appear before instructions in macro body.

REPT -- repeat N times (count must be numeric literal, not symbol):
  REPT 5 / ... / ENDM

IRP -- iterate over angle-bracket list:
  IRP reg, <AX, BX, CX, DX> / ... / ENDM

Nesting: macros can invoke other macros. REPT/IRP can appear inside macros.
Expansion iterates up to 10,000 iterations. Self-recursive macros will hit limit.

Restrictions:
  - Macro names cannot shadow reserved words
  - Redefining a macro emits warning
  - Argument count mismatch emits warning (missing -> empty, extras ignored)
  - REPT count must be literal, not symbol or expression

@@EXAMPLES
PrintChar MACRO ch / MOV DL, ch / MOV AH, 02h / INT 21h / ENDM
MakeLabel MACRO name, num / name&num: / DB 0 / ENDM
Skip MACRO / LOCAL done / JMP done / NOP / done: / ENDM
REPT 5 / NOP / ENDM
IRP reg, <AX, BX, CX, DX> / PUSH reg / ENDM
@@END

@@TOPIC structs
@@GROUP reference
@@BRIEF STRUC/ENDS definitions with field offsets and instance allocation.
@@RELATED directives, syntax

Define named data structures with automatic field offset calculation (MASM-compatible).

Definition (no code emitted, creates offset constants):
  name STRUC / fields / name ENDS

Field types: DB (1 byte), DW (2 bytes), DD (4 bytes), RESB n, RESW n.

Using offsets in expressions:
  MOV AX, [BX + POINT.X]
  ADD BX, POINT              ; advance pointer by struct size

Instance allocation with angle-bracket overrides:
  pt1 POINT <100, 200>       emits DW 100, DW 200
  pt2 POINT <>                emits defaults
  pt3 POINT <10>              partial: first field=10, rest=defaults

Skipped fields use defaults: <10, , 30> overrides first and third, keeps second.

@@EXAMPLES
POINT STRUC / X DW 0 / Y DW 0 / POINT ENDS
pt1 POINT <100, 200>
MOV AX, [BX + POINT.X]
@@END

@@TOPIC instructions
@@GROUP reference
@@BRIEF Full instruction set by category.
@@RELATED --explain, --dump-isa, addressing

Data movement:
  MOV   reg/mem/sreg combinations    XCHG  reg<->reg, reg<->mem
  LEA   reg16<-mem                   PUSH  reg16, mem16, sreg
  POP   reg16, mem16, sreg           PUSHA/POPA  all regs (80186+)
  PUSHF/POPF  flags register         XLAT  AL=[BX+AL] table lookup
  IN    AL/AX<-port                  OUT   port<-AL/AX

Arithmetic:
  ADD ADC SUB SBB  reg/mem/imm combinations
  CMP    like SUB, flags only        INC DEC  reg/mem (preserves CF)
  NEG    two's complement            MUL IMUL  unsigned/signed multiply
  DIV IDIV  unsigned/signed divide   CBW  sign-extend AL->AX
  CWD    sign-extend AX->DX:AX

Logic:
  AND OR XOR  reg/mem/imm            NOT  bitwise invert
  TEST  like AND, flags only

Shift/rotate:
  SHL/SAL SHR SAR  shift left/right
  ROL ROR RCL RCR  rotate
  Forms: reg/mem,1  reg/mem,CL  reg/mem,imm (imm>1 = 80186+)

Flags: CLC STC CMC CLD STD CLI STI LAHF SAHF
Misc:  NOP XLAT/XLATB HLT

Control flow:
  JMP   near, indirect (reg16/mem16)
  CALL  near, indirect (reg16/mem16)
  RET   return from call
  Jcc   all conditional jumps (auto-promoted beyond short range)
  LOOP  dec CX, jump if CX!=0 (short range only, NOT auto-promoted)
  LOOPE/LOOPZ  LOOPNE/LOOPNZ  JCXZ

String: MOVSB/W CMPSB/W STOSB/W LODSB/W SCASB/W
Prefix: REP/REPE/REPZ REPNE/REPNZ

Interrupts: INT imm8

@@EXAMPLES
agent86 --explain MOV
agent86 --explain IMUL
agent86 --dump-isa
@@END

@@TOPIC addressing
@@GROUP reference
@@BRIEF 8086 addressing modes and segment overrides.
@@RELATED syntax, instructions

The 8086 supports these base/index register combinations in memory operands:

  R/M  Registers    Default Segment
   0   [BX+SI]      DS
   1   [BX+DI]      DS
   2   [BP+SI]      SS
   3   [BP+DI]      SS
   4   [SI]         DS
   5   [DI]         DS
   6   [BP]         SS (direct addr if no base)
   7   [BX]         DS

Each can have an optional displacement: [BX+SI+10h]
Direct addressing: [100h] uses DS by default.

Segment overrides:
  MOV AX, ES:[BX]       ; prefix form
  MOV AX, [ES:BX]       ; inside brackets

Only BX, BP, SI, DI are valid in memory operands.
AX, CX, DX, SP are NOT valid inside [] brackets.

BP-based addressing defaults to SS; all others default to DS.

@@EXAMPLES
MOV AX, [BX+SI+10h]
MOV AX, ES:[BX]
MOV AX, [100h]
MOV AX, [BP+DI]
@@END

@@TOPIC interrupts
@@GROUP interrupts
@@BRIEF Overview of all emulated interrupts.
@@RELATED int10h, int16h, int20h, int21h, int33h

The emulator handles these interrupts. All others are logged in skipped[].

INT 10h  BIOS Video Services
  Set/get cursor, scroll window, write characters, teletype output, video mode.
  8KB VRAM at segment B800h (80x50 CGA text mode, char+attr per cell).

INT 16h  BIOS Keyboard Services
  AH=02h: get shift flags in AL (bit 0=RShift, 1=LShift, 2=Ctrl, 3=Alt).

INT 20h  Program Terminate
  Halts emulation with exitCode 0. Standard .COM termination.

INT 21h  DOS Function Calls
  28 functions: console I/O, system info, file handle I/O, directory operations.

INT 33h  Mouse Services
  Position, buttons, ranges, visibility. Enabled by --mouse or --events.

@@EXAMPLES
agent86 --help int10h
agent86 --help int21h
agent86 --help int33h
@@END

@@TOPIC int10h
@@GROUP interrupts
@@BRIEF BIOS video services (INT 10h).
@@RELATED interrupts, attributes, screen-capture

VRAM: 8KB at segment B800h, 80x50 text mode. Each cell = 2 bytes (char + attr).

  AH=00h  Set video mode     AL=mode (only mode 3 meaningful). Clears screen.
  AH=02h  Set cursor pos     DH=row, DL=col, BH=page (ignored)
  AH=03h  Get cursor pos     Returns DH=row, DL=col, CX=shape
  AH=06h  Scroll up          AL=lines (0=clear), BH=fill attr, CH,CL=top, DH,DL=bottom
  AH=07h  Scroll down        Same params as 06h, scrolls downward
  AH=08h  Read char/attr     Returns AL=char, AH=attr at cursor
  AH=09h  Write char+attr    AL=char, BL=attr, CX=count. No cursor advance.
  AH=0Ah  Write char only    AL=char, CX=count. Keeps existing attr. No advance.
  AH=0Eh  Teletype output    AL=char. Writes and advances cursor. Handles CR/LF/BS.
  AH=0Fh  Get video mode     Returns AL=3, AH=80, BH=0

@@EXAMPLES
MOV AX, 0600h / MOV BH, 1Fh / XOR CX, CX / MOV DH, 24 / MOV DL, 79 / INT 10h
MOV AH, 02h / MOV DH, 5 / MOV DL, 10 / XOR BH, BH / INT 10h
MOV AH, 0Eh / MOV AL, 'A' / INT 10h
@@END

@@TOPIC int16h
@@GROUP interrupts
@@BRIEF BIOS keyboard services (INT 16h).
@@RELATED interrupts, --input, --events

  AH=02h  Get shift flags    Returns AL = shift flags byte

Shift flags byte (AL):
  Bit 0: Right Shift held
  Bit 1: Left Shift held
  Bit 2: Ctrl held (not yet emulated)
  Bit 3: Alt held (not yet emulated)
  Bit 4-7: Lock states (not emulated)

Shift state is driven by \S prefix in --input or event keys strings.
  \SA          delivers 'A' with Left Shift (bit 1) set
  \S\x00\S\x4B  extended key with shift held for both bytes
  Unshifted keys clear the shift flags.

@@EXAMPLES
MOV AH, 02h / INT 16h / AND AL, 03h / JNZ shifted
agent86 --run-source arrows.asm --input "\S\x00\S\x4B"
@@END

@@TOPIC int20h
@@GROUP interrupts
@@BRIEF Program termination (INT 20h).
@@RELATED interrupts, int21h

INT 20h halts emulation with exitCode 0. This is the standard .COM termination.

A program that returns with an empty stack (RET when SP=FFFEh) will execute the
INT 20h placed at address 0000h (PSP stub) by the emulator.

Alternative: INT 21h/4Ch exits with a return code in AL.

@@EXAMPLES
INT 20h
MOV AH, 4Ch / MOV AL, 0 / INT 21h
@@END

@@TOPIC int21h
@@GROUP interrupts
@@BRIEF DOS function calls (INT 21h) -- all subfunctions.
@@RELATED interrupts, file-io, --dos-root, --input

31 implemented functions in five categories.

Console I/O:
  AH=01h  Read char with echo    -> AL=char (0Dh if input exhausted)
  AH=02h  Write character        DL=char -> output
  AH=06h  Direct console I/O     DL=FFh: read (ZF=0+AL if avail, ZF=1 if not)
                                  DL!=FFh: write DL to output
  AH=09h  Write $-string         DS:DX=string, prints until '$'. Cap: 4096 bytes.

System:
  AH=0Eh  Select disk            DL=drive (0=A,2=C) -> AL=26
  AH=19h  Get current disk       -> AL=drive (default 2=C:)
  AH=1Ah  Set DTA                DS:DX=address
  AH=25h  Set interrupt vector   stub, silently ignored
  AH=2Ah  Get date               -> CX=year, DH=month, DL=day, AL=dow
  AH=2Ch  Get time               -> CH=hr, CL=min, DH=sec, DL=csec
  AH=2Fh  Get DTA                -> ES:BX=DTA address (default PSP:0080h)
  AH=30h  Get DOS version        -> AL=5, AH=0 (DOS 5.0)
  AH=35h  Get interrupt vector   stub -> ES:BX=0000:0000
  AH=62h  Get PSP segment        -> BX=0

Memory management:
  AH=48h  Allocate memory        BX=paragraphs -> AX=segment (CF=0)
                                  On failure: CF=1, AX=8, BX=largest free
  AH=49h  Free memory            ES=segment -> CF=0 on success
                                  On failure: CF=1, AX=9 (invalid block)
  AH=4Ah  Resize memory block    ES=segment, BX=new paragraphs -> CF=0
                                  On failure: CF=1, AX=8, BX=largest free

File handle I/O (handles 5+ require --dos-root):
  AH=3Ch  Create file            DS:DX=path, CX=attr -> AX=handle
  AH=3Dh  Open file              DS:DX=path, AL=mode(0=r,1=w,2=rw) -> AX=handle
  AH=3Eh  Close file             BX=handle
  AH=3Fh  Read                   BX=handle, CX=count, DS:DX=buf -> AX=bytes
  AH=40h  Write                  BX=handle, CX=count, DS:DX=buf -> AX=bytes
  AH=42h  Seek                   BX=handle, AL=origin(0/1/2), CX:DX=offset -> DX:AX
  AH=43h  Get/set attrs          AL=0:get->CX, AL=1:set(stub)
  AH=44h/00 IOCTL get info       BX=handle -> DX=info word
  AH=44h/09 IOCTL block remote   BL=drive -> DX=0(local) for C:
  AH=57h  Get file date/time     AL=0, BX=handle -> CX=time, DX=date
  AH=4Ch  Exit with code         AL=exit code

Directory (require --dos-root):
  AH=3Bh  Change directory       DS:DX=path
  AH=47h  Get current directory  DS:SI=buf, DL=drive
  AH=4Eh  FindFirst              DS:DX=pattern, CX=attr mask -> DTA
  AH=4Fh  FindNext               -> DTA

Error convention: CF=1 on failure, AX = error code.
  1=invalid, 2=not found, 3=path not found, 5=denied, 6=bad handle, 18=no more

@@EXAMPLES
MOV AH, 09h / MOV DX, msg / INT 21h
MOV AH, 01h / INT 21h
MOV AH, 4Ch / MOV AL, 0 / INT 21h
MOV AH, 3Dh / MOV AL, 0 / MOV DX, filename / INT 21h / JC error
MOV AH, 4Eh / MOV CX, 0 / MOV DX, pattern / INT 21h / JC done
MOV AH, 48h / MOV BX, 100h / INT 21h / JC error  ; allocate 256 paragraphs (4KB)
MOV ES, AX / MOV AH, 49h / INT 21h               ; free the block
@@END

@@TOPIC int33h
@@GROUP interrupts
@@BRIEF Mouse services (INT 33h).
@@RELATED --mouse, --events, interaction

Enabled by --mouse or --events with mouse actions. Dispatches on full AX register.

  AX=0000h  Reset/detect        -> AX=FFFFh (installed), BX=3 (buttons)
  AX=0001h  Show cursor         sets visible flag
  AX=0002h  Hide cursor         clears visible flag
  AX=0003h  Get position/btns   -> BX=buttons, CX=x, DX=y
  AX=0004h  Set position        CX=x, DX=y (clamped to range)
  AX=0005h  Button press info   BX=btn -> BX=count, AX=btns, CX=x, DX=y
  AX=0006h  Button release info same as 0005h for releases
  AX=0007h  Set horiz range     CX=min, DX=max
  AX=0008h  Set vert range      CX=min, DX=max
  AX=000Bh  Get motion          -> CX=0, DX=0 (not tracked)
  AX=000Ch  Set event handler   silently ignored

Without --mouse/--events: AX=0000h returns AX=0 (not installed).

@@EXAMPLES
MOV AX, 3 / INT 33h
agent86 --run-source mouse.asm --mouse 320,100,1
agent86 --run-source app.asm --events '[{"on":"poll:3","mouse":[320,100,1]}]'
@@END

@@TOPIC json
@@GROUP schemas
@@BRIEF Overview of all JSON output formats.
@@RELATED json-agent, json-run, json-disassemble

All modes emit structured JSON to stdout (or --output-file).

--agent output:
  {success, diagnostics[], symbols{}, listing[], includes[]}

--run-source output:
  {assembly: {success, size, diagnostics[]},
   emulation: {success, halted, haltReason, exitCode, cyclesExecuted,
               fidelity, output, outputHex, finalState, skipped[],
               screen[], screenAttrs[], screenshot, events, fileIO, diagnostics[]}}

--run output:
  Same as emulation section of --run-source, plus finalState.sregs and flagBits.
  snapshots[] included when --breakpoints or --watch-regs used.

--disassemble output:
  {file, fileSize, instructions[], dataRegions[]}

--explain output:
  {mnemonic, found, forms[]}

--dump-isa output:
  [{mnemonic, desc}, ...]

Error output (any mode):
  {"error": "message"}

@@EXAMPLES
agent86 --help json-agent
agent86 --help json-run
agent86 --help json-disassemble
@@END

@@TOPIC json-agent
@@GROUP schemas
@@BRIEF --agent output schema: success, diagnostics, symbols, listing.
@@RELATED --agent, json

Schema for --agent JSON output:

{
  "success": true|false,
  "diagnostics": [
    {"level":"ERROR|WARNING|INFO", "line":N, "msg":"...", "hint":"...",
     "file":"..." (with INCLUDE), "sourceLine":N (with INCLUDE)}
  ],
  "symbols": {
    "NAME": {"val":N, "type":"LABEL|EQU", "line":N,
             "file":"..." (with INCLUDE), "sourceLine":N}
  },
  "listing": [
    {"addr":N, "line":N, "size":N, "decoded":"...", "src":"...",
     "bytes":[...], "file":"..." (with INCLUDE), "sourceLine":N}
  ],
  "includes": ["file1.asm", ...]
}

Key fields:
  success       true = binary produced, false = errors occurred
  hint          always present, contains actionable fix for agents
  decoded       how assembler interpreted instruction (compare vs intent)
  bytes         raw machine code as decimal integers

@@EXAMPLES
agent86 --agent source.asm
@@END

@@TOPIC json-run
@@GROUP schemas
@@BRIEF --run / --run-source emulation output schema.
@@RELATED --run, --run-source, json

Emulation output fields (in --run-source under "emulation", in --run at top level):

  success          true if emulator ran without internal errors
  halted           true if program terminated
  haltReason       "INT 20h program terminate", "INT 21h/4Ch exit (code=N)",
                   "HLT instruction at 0xNNNN", "Cycle limit reached (N)",
                   "Division by zero", "Division overflow"
  exitCode         from INT 21h/4Ch AL, or 0 for INT 20h
  cyclesExecuted   instruction count (= --max-cycles means possible infinite loop)
  fidelity         0.0-1.0 ratio of emulated vs total instructions
  output           text output (INT 21h/02h,06h,09h). Capped at 4096 bytes.
  outputHex        same output as hex string for binary-safe inspection
  finalState       {registers{AX..DI}, IP, flags, flagBits (--run), cursor{row,col},
                    sregs (--run), mouse{x,y,buttons,visible} (when mouse enabled)}
  skipped[]        [{instruction, reason}] for unhandled instructions
  snapshots[]      breakpoint/watchpoint state captures
  screen[]         VRAM text (with --screen/--viewport)
  screenAttrs[]    attribute hex (with --attrs)
  screenshot       BMP path (with --screenshot)
  events           {total, fired, pending, log[]} (with --events)
  fileIO           {filesOpened, filesClosed, bytesRead, bytesWritten,
                    dirSearches, errors} (with --dos-root)
  diagnostics[]    runtime diagnostics

@@EXAMPLES
agent86 --run-source source.asm
agent86 --run program.com
@@END

@@TOPIC json-disassemble
@@GROUP schemas
@@BRIEF --disassemble output schema.
@@RELATED --disassemble, json

Schema for --disassemble JSON output:

{
  "file": "output.com",
  "fileSize": 93,
  "instructions": [
    {"addr":N, "bytes":[...], "hex":"B8 05 00", "asm":"MOV AX, 0x0005", "size":3}
  ],
  "dataRegions": [
    {"addr":N, "bytes":[...], "hex":"48 65 6C", "size":3,
     "msg":"Decode failed or ambiguous"}
  ]
}

Uses linear sweep (sequential decode from offset 0).
Immediates in uppercase hex with 0x prefix.
Jump targets as absolute addresses.
String data (DB) appears in dataRegions.

@@EXAMPLES
agent86 --disassemble output.com
@@END

@@TOPIC errors
@@GROUP diagnostics
@@BRIEF Error diagnostic reference with causes and fixes.
@@RELATED warnings, --agent

Every error includes an actionable hint field. Read the hint first.

Common errors:
  "Undefined label X" + "Did you mean 0XH?"
    Hex literal missing leading zero. Write 0FFh not FFh.

  "Undefined label X" + "Did you mean 'Y'?"
    Typo in label name. Hint shows closest matching symbol.

  "Undefined label X" + registers hint
    Register used in expression. Registers can't appear in arithmetic.

  "Undefined label X" + local labels hint
    .label used outside PROC. Wrap in PROC/ENDP or use global label.

  "Loop jump out of range (N)"
    Loop body exceeds 127 bytes. Use DEC CX / JNZ target instead.

  "Size mismatch between operands"
    Mixing 8-bit and 16-bit registers. Hint shows both sizes.

  "Stack ops require 16-bit register"
    PUSH AL etc. Hint shows 16-bit counterpart.

  "POP CS is not a valid instruction"
    Use far JMP or far CALL to change CS.

  "Invalid operands for X"
    Wrong operand combination. Hint shows all valid forms.

  "Invalid numeric literal: X"
    Malformed number. Hint shows invalid character and valid format.

  "Invalid register in memory operand: X"
    Used AX/CX/DX/SP inside []. Valid: BX, BP, SI, DI.

  "Invalid addressing mode combination"
    Illegal register pair. Hint shows all valid 8086 modes.

  "PROC without label"
    Example: myproc: PROC

  "Extra tokens at end of line"
    Missing comma, stray character, or comment without ;

  "LEA requires 16-bit register"
    Use AX..DI, not AL..BH.

  "Division by zero"
    Check divisor value or EQU constant.

  Macro errors: "without matching ENDM", "reserved name", "iteration limit"

@@END

@@TOPIC warnings
@@GROUP diagnostics
@@BRIEF Warning diagnostic reference. Assembly succeeds but issues flagged.
@@RELATED errors, --agent

Warnings mean assembly succeeded but something may be wrong.

  "uses 80186+ encoding"
    Shift/rotate with imm > 1. Hint shows MOV CL,N / SHL reg,CL replacement.

  "No size prefix on memory-immediate"
    MOV [BX], 5 without BYTE/WORD. Add BYTE or WORD prefix.

  "No size prefix on memory shift/rotate"
    SHL [BX], 1 without BYTE/WORD. Add BYTE or WORD prefix.

  "truncated to 8-bit" / "truncated to 16-bit"
    Immediate exceeds range. Hint shows truncated result and valid range.

  "ORG directive after code"
    ORG doesn't move already-emitted code. Place ORG at start.

  "redefined"
    Label defined more than once. Hint shows previous definition line.

  "Local label outside procedure"
    .label used without PROC/ENDP. Wrap in PROC/ENDP or use global label.

  "Macro 'X' redefined"
    Second definition replaces first. Hint shows previous line.

  "Macro 'X' invoked with N args, expected M"
    Missing args become empty strings; extras ignored.

  "Conditional jump auto-promoted"
    Jcc target beyond short range. Assembler auto-emitted inverted Jcc + near JMP.
    INFO-level, not an error. Jump now uses 5 bytes instead of 2.

@@END

@@TOPIC attributes
@@GROUP reference
@@BRIEF CGA text-mode attribute byte and color table.
@@RELATED int10h, --attrs, screen-capture

CGA attribute byte format (1 byte per VRAM cell):
  Bit 7      Blink
  Bits 6-4   Background color (0-7)
  Bits 3-0   Foreground color (0-15)

Color values:
  0  Black          8  Dark Grey
  1  Blue           9  Light Blue
  2  Green          A  Light Green
  3  Cyan           B  Light Cyan
  4  Red            C  Light Red
  5  Magenta        D  Light Magenta
  6  Brown          E  Yellow
  7  Light Grey     F  White

Common attribute values:
  07h  light grey on black (default)
  0Fh  bright white on black
  1Fh  white on blue
  4Eh  yellow on red
  00h  black on black (invisible!)

Formula: attr = (background << 4) | foreground  (add 80h for blink)

@@EXAMPLES
MOV AX, 0B800h / MOV ES, AX / MOV BYTE ES:[0], 'A' / MOV BYTE ES:[1], 1Fh
agent86 --run-source colors.asm --screen --attrs
@@END
